title: For Sale:  Juggernaut Arms - CETME .308 Battle Rifle
postcontent:
Manufacture: Century Arms
Model: Cetme
Caliber: 7.62x51 NATO
Type: Semi-Automatic, Magazine fed
Capacity: 20+1

Having test fired this rifle, it functions flawlessly.  It is very powerful, accurate and a lot of fun to shoot.

In the late 90's Century Arms International (CAI) began offering semiautomatic only civilian versions known as the CETME Sporter, which are manufactured from assembled military surplus and US made parts. Although largely built from Model "C" parts, there have been reports of model "B" parts in the Model "C" Century built rifles.
Due to the restrictions against importing receivers of select fire weapons, all receivers for these civilian versions are made in the US. Earlier receivers were cast steel, while later receivers were made from stamped and welded steel. Earlier rifles retained the wood furniture of the originals while later examples were available with Heckler & Koch style composite stocks. Due to state and local laws restricting weapons with assault rifle features, the CETME Sporter is also available with a permanently pinned muzzle brake rather than the original flash hider. Both civilian .308 Winchester and NATO 7.62x51mm ammunition may safely be used in the CETME sporter.
Reviews of the reliability and accuracy of these civilian versions have been mixed, with earlier versions generally being considered more reliable and accurate than later examples.

The original bolt was thought to be lost, but recently resurfaced when accidentally dug up from the property where it had inadvertently fallen out of the rifle years before.  As would be expected, the original bolt resembles a dug relic from the Civil War, and likely cannot be salvaged despite repeated attempts to do so with PB  Blaster and any and all other home remedies.

In light of the above, I'm seeking a replacement bolt if anyone has an extra one from a parts gun.  While I would prefer a bolt made for this particular rifle, I would also consider any other bolt that would work if one exists for a similar rifle that would fit and function in this  rifle and that wouldn't look too out of place on this gun.  

I've put a price here simply because ArmsList appears to require a number in order to post a listing, but I also realize that any price would be negotiable depending upon what is available and the nature of any solution that might work. 

I would prefer a local sale and face-to-face transaction so I can ensure that any replacement or substitute bolt will work, in order to minimize the hassle facto for all concerned, and to save both parties any shipping or related costs.  

I've posted photos of the rifle here in case anyone reading this with more expertise and knowledge on this than I have (which is likely anyone reading this) can provide any information or guidance.

I realize I may be searching for a needle in a haystack, but any guidance or assistance would be greatly appreciated.  Thanks in advance.

title: For Sale:  Iver Johnson 55 Target .22 Revolver (great plinker)
location: Near I-55 & I-80 (Grundy County), Chicago, Illinois
postcontent:
This is a double action that looks like a single action.  Cylinder removes for loading and unloading.  8 shots of .22 LR, Longs, or Shorts.  6" barrel with fixed sights, but they are right on target. 

The bluing is not in the best shape.  There was a moderate amount of light rust on the barrel from sitting in a soft case (learned about that the hard way!).  Also some scattered light rust on the cylinder and frame.  I removed it with oil and fine steel wool but the light pitting is still there.  It looks better than my description sounds, but it should be stored with a light wipe of oil to prevent any return of rust.

It's a nice shooter, though.  Quite accurate, with a nice crisp trigger when shot in single action.  Just a good little accurate plinker at a great price.

gold engravings of Sam Colt, Ben

exact replica of the original presented to 
Major Ben McCulloch in 1848. Extremely 
hard to find collectible. Also comes with 
walnut display case, powder flask, bullet 
mold and nipple wrench. This is number 399 
of 1000.
